The production-script preamble.

By default, bash is remarkably forgiving, and for serious scripts that forgiveness is a liability. Out of the box, a command that fails does not stop the script; a reference to a variable that was never set quietly expands to nothing; and a failure partway through a pipeline is swallowed as long as the last stage succeeds. For production scripts you want the opposite behaviour: fail fast and fail loud. The canonical preamble that achieves this is the set command with three options, e, u, and o pipefail, often followed by a tightened field separator.

Let us take the three in turn. Set dash e, called error-exit, makes the script stop the instant any command fails, instead of blundering onward after, say, a failed copy. Set dash u, called no-unset, turns a reference to an undefined variable into an error, which catches typos in variable names at the moment they would otherwise silently misbehave. And set dash o pipefail changes a pipeline's exit code so that it reflects the first stage that failed, not merely the last stage; without it, a failing command piped into a successful grep would wrongly report overall success. Tightening the field separator to just newline and tab, dropping the space, makes word-splitting safer when filenames contain spaces.

There is one more thing to know: how to deliberately allow a command to fail without bringing the whole script down. You can wrap it in an explicit if test, checking for failure yourself, or you can temporarily switch the error-exit option off with set plus e, run the risky command, capture its exit code, and switch the option back on. And when a script misbehaves, the debugging companion is set dash x, which prints each command, with its variables expanded, just before running it, so you can watch exactly what the script is doing. Turn it on at the top, or sprinkle it around the trouble spot and turn it off again afterward.
